    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey quick question for my civ eng class. if concrete is already really strong, why do we actually need to put steel rebar inside it for foundations? like what's the actual mechanical reason?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Concrete is strong in compression but weak in tension, so it cracks easily when pulled apart. Steel rebar has high tensile strength, allowing it to absorb the pulling forces that concrete cannot. This combination creates a composite material that can handle both compression and tension, which is essential for structural integrity under load. Without the steel, the foundation would split and fail under stress, even if the concrete itself is very strong.",
