    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so it's basically about how they handle different types of force. is there any specific way they work together internally, like how the bond between them works so the steel doesn't just slip out of the concrete when it's under tension?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, the bond is crucial, and it works through a combination of mechanical interlocking and chemical adhesion. The rough surface of the rebar creates tiny grooves that the concrete fills and hardens around, locking the steel in place physically. Additionally, when concrete cures, a chemical bond forms at the interface, ensuring that as the concrete tries to expand, it pulls the steel along with it. This synergy prevents slippage, allowing the two materials to act as a single unit under stress.\n\nWithout this bond, the steel would simply slip out of the concrete like a loose bolt, rendering the foundation useless. It is a perfect example of how different materials can work together if the connection is strong enough.",
